tibis inparibus. We may conceive roughly the appearance of the tibicen by picturing a man with two stunted clarionets in his mouth. If both were dextrae or both sinistrae they were called tibiae pares The dextra had a shrill treble, the sinistra a deep bass tone3 these tones indicating the change in the character of the drama. The comedy tibis imparibus would imply a change from stataria to motoria, ‘from grave to gay, from lively to severe’, and this corresponds with the alter- natione in the Phormio.
